Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog** — Override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points: `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks — without it you'd have a race condition. Call `args.Cancel()` to block navigation, then `deferral.Complete()` to release.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — In `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard dialog still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Since the `CancelCommand` uses `GoToAsync("..")`, it flows through `OnNavigating` and your unsaved-changes guard still applies. Alternatively, you can put the confirmation logic directly in the command and skip the guard for that path.
